    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "c456b4102731f8d2e9f633cb253a58f065e5cf57bc1e7d6024f2b4f61970f641",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "A positive answer to this would give an answer to the second part of [382]. Heuristically, the 'probability' that $n$ has no prime divisors $\\geq n^{1/2}$ is $1-\\log 2>0$, so standard heuristics predict the answer to this is yes."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "ed2612201974f950d4395b6885588581acdc7348084e2e15f8cd5b6eb6c654a8",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Is it true that for every $k$ there are infinitely many primes $p$ such that the largest prime divisor of\\[\\prod_{0\\leq i\\leq k}(p^2+i)\\]is $p$?"
    }
  },
